Took a slightly different approach and used the lemon juice etc. mixture as a marinade for a whole chicken (several hours)and grilled it on the rotisserie of our gas Weber. I used only half of the salt, but it could have used the entire amount. I didn't make additional sauce, but next time I will as the flavors were good but I think the additional boost f fresh to dip in or pour over would be great. Made a quick side dish by quartering some baking potatoes, sprinkling with a little olive oil, kosher salt and fresh chopped garlic and baking at 350° in a pan lined with parchment paper (easy clean up). The garlic got a bit too brown for my liking before the potatoes were completely done, so would add it a bit later another time.

Rating: 4
This is an excellent recipe! I brined boneless, skinless thighs and skinned legs for two hours before grilling. Having brined the chicken, I did not season with salt before grilling. The dressing was delicious -- the fresh oregano is key here. All in all, the best grilled chicken recipe I've made in a long time.

Rating: 3
I disagree that this recipe is time consuming. It just looks like it because of the very specific grilling instructions. Just grill the chicken the way you like it and dunk it in the sauce. I like it better this way than marinating in the sauce and grilling because there are fewer flare-ups caused by the dripping marinade. I love this recipe.

Rating: 3
This sounds like a great recipe, although incredibly time consuming! I do the same recipe often and much quicker. Mix the lemon juice, oregano, fresh garlic and olive oil together and let the chicken (I usually use just breasts) marinate a while then grill until done. Same result, succulent, delicious chicken!

